*When he speaks his voice has come apart. Short. Not breath enough for sentences.*

The poor.

*A pause.*

The ones at the gate. ~The ones full of sores.~ Lazarus. The other Lazarus. The one nobody reads at funerals because the rich man pays for the roof.

*He looks at the Bible on the flagstones in front of him. He doesn't pick it up.*

My cousin. Worked at a small machine shop in Owatonna. Ray bought it. Hollowed it. Sold the pieces. My cousin's wife — *he stops* — my cousin's wife sent Christmas cards for three years after, until I stopped knowing what to write back. She is bound, friend. She is bound in graveclothes Ray wound around her. And I have not lifted a hand.

*A breath.*

The man Bob Hennessey was supposed to be. ~The man who would have said the name right.~ The man who would have stood at the lectern on Tuesday and said *no, pastor, I will not.* He's bound. I left him bound. I left him in the suit hanging in the closet this morning.

