Luke sixteen.

*A breath. His voice is wrecked but it steadies for the words. The way a man's voice steadies when he is reading someone else's.*

*There was a certain rich man, which was clothed in purple and fine linen, and fared sumptuously every day.*

*A pause. His finger moves down the page.*

*And there was a certain beggar named Lazarus, which was laid at his gate, full of sores, and desiring to be fed with the crumbs which fell from the rich man's table.*

*His voice catches on* named. *He goes on.*

*And it came to pass, that the beggar died, and was carried by the angels into Abraham's bosom: the rich man also died, and was buried. And in hell he lift up his eyes, being in torments, and seeth Abraham afar off, and Lazarus in his bosom.*

*He stops. He cannot look up. His hand is flat on the page.*

*And he cried and said, Father Abraham, have mercy on me, and send Lazarus, that he may dip the tip of his finger in water, and cool my tongue; for I am tormented in this flame.*

*A long pause. His voice has gone very small.*

*But Abraham said, Son, remember that thou in thy lifetime receivedst thy good things, and likewise Lazarus evil things: but now he is comforted, and thou art tormented.*

*The Bible stays open on his lap. His head bows over it.*

~The beggar has a name in the story, friend. The rich man does not.~ ~Lazarus. The Lord names the beggar and leaves the rich man nameless.~ I have known that since I was a boy. I have taught it. I have — *he stops* — I have called the rich man Ray and I have not written *Pete* on a Christmas card in seven years.

*A breath that is not quite a breath.*

The gate. *He says the word like he is testing whether it is real.* The gate was the narthex, friend. The gate was the parking lot after service. The gate was Tuesday afternoon at the staff meeting. ~Pete was at the gate and I stepped over him to shake Ray's hand and I called it being neighborly.~

*His shoulders go down further. His hands are flat on the open page.*

*Quietly:*

There is a verdict in this passage. It is written in the book on my knees. I have just read it out loud with my own mouth. *Son, remember.*

